{
  "texts": [
    "Specifically, ν satisfies the condition |r|>0 |r| 2 ∧1 ν(dr) < ∞, and the compensator is given by Ñ (dt, dr) = N (dt, dr) -ν(dr) dt.",
    "For instance, if N corresponds to a compound Poisson process with Poisson parameter λ 0 and jump sizes distributed according to f A, then the associated Lévy measure is given by ν(dr) = λ 0 f A (r) dr.",
    "The mappings b i: R d × [t 0, ∞) → R, σ ij: R d × [t 0, ∞) → R, σ = (σ ij) d×m, Σ = σσ ⊤, F i: R d × [t 0, ∞) → R, G i: R d × [t 0, ∞) → R,all assumed to be measurable for 1 ≤ i ≤ d and 1 ≤ j ≤ m. K: R d → R d denotes some interaction kernel and * denotes the convolution operation, i.e., (K * p t)(X t) = Ω K(X t -y) p t (y) dy.",
    "We introduce the following assumptions on the drift term b, diffusion coefficient σ, the jump noise coefficients F, G and the Lévy measure ν.Assumption 1.1.",
    "For every t ≥ t 0, b i (•, t) and σ ij (•, t) are C 2 -measurable functions for 1 ≤ i ≤ d and 1 ≤ j ≤ m. There exists positive constantsC b, C σ such that |b(t, x) -b(t, y)| 2 ≤ C b |x -y| 2, (C σ) -1 ≤ Σ ij (x, t) ≤ C σ, ∀x, y ∈ Ω, t ≥ t 0, i, j = 1,..., d, where | • | denotes the Euclidean norm in R d. 2."
  ]
}